    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-06-14T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-06-14T16:00:00-05:00" n="109"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d109">
                <head>109. Record of Meeting Between President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                        >Kennedy</persName> and the Permanent Representative to the North Atlantic
                    Council (<persName corresp="#p_FTK1">Finletter</persName>)<note n="0"
                        type="source" xml:id="d109fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>. Secret. No drafting information appears
                        on the source text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-06-14T17:00:00-04:00">June 14, 1961, 5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Also present: Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>, Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_AD1">Acheson</persName>, Deputy Secretary Gilpatric, Assistant
                    Secretary <persName corresp="#p_NP2">Nitze</persName>, Assistant Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>, Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_OHD1"
                        >Owen</persName>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FTK1">Finletter</persName> emphasized the need
                        for greater civilian control by the North Atlantic Council over <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> military programs.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> indicated that Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_SDU1">Stikker</persName> might wish to strengthen
                        his International Staff to facilitate civilian control. Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SDU1">Stikker</persName> had spoken of the possible need for
                        a high level assistant who would help him in negotiating <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> military programs with individual <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> countries.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FTK1">Finletter</persName> spoke of the
                        differences between <persName corresp="#p_NLGL1">General
                        Norstad</persName>’s views and the new U.S. policy which Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_FTK1">Finletter</persName> was representing. The President
                        asked for a fuller description of these differences. Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_AD1"
                            >Acheson</persName>, and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NP2">Nitze</persName>
                        indicated that they centered on, but were not limited to, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NLGL1">General Norstad</persName>’s desire for 500 land
                        based <gloss target="#t_MRBM1">MRBM</gloss>s. This desire was inconsistent
                        with existing U.S. policy, which holds that there is enough nuclear power
                        already programmed for Europe and that a large new <gloss target="#t_MRBM1"
                            >MRBM</gloss> program would absorb such energies and resources as to
                        prevent needed improvement in existing conventional forces.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The President stressed the importance of making clear to the Europeans
                        that the projected improvement in conventional forces did not imply any
                        weakening in its use of nuclear weapons. He asked that a letter to <persName
                            corresp="#p_NLGL1">General Norstad</persName> be prepared making the
                        point.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
